\subsection{Phage Genome Analysis}
The computational analysis of phage genomes has evolved from alignment-based sequence matching to feature-learning approaches. Traditional methods, such as BLAST~\cite{altschul1990basic}, rely on homology search against reference databases like GenBank~\citep{benson2018genbank}. These methods are highly effective at identifying sequences with no homology to known references. To address this, learning-based approaches have been developed~\cite{camargo2024identification,peng2024viralm}. VirSorter2~\cite{guo2021virsorter2} integrates multiple classifiers to capture diverse viral signals, while CheckV~\cite{nayfach2021checkv} assesses genome completeness based on gene content and terminal repeats. However, these discriminative models typically output binary classifications without biological reasoning and often specialized for a single task. Our work investigates whether general-purpose LLMs can bridge this gap by leveraging their inherent reasoning capabilities to analyze raw genomic sequences directly.

